{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_melville_ver02/data/sn84026749/00222254024/1923090401/0484.xml":{"full_text":"22\nHE DOTH TOLL\nIIJHOOE\nTOFRIGHT\nScientist Tells How It Is Pos\nsible to Avert 111 Effects of\nGreat Earth Tremors.\nBy WILLIAM PARKER.\nCosmopolitan News Service.\nPASADENA. Calif., Sept. 4.\u2014 The\ngreat loss of life in the Japanese\nearthquakes was ascribed to fear\nand poverty when Ralph Arnold,\nchairman of the Southern Califon\nnia section of the Seismological So\nciety of America, today told the\ncause of earth tremors and how\nman eventually will triumph over\nthese freaks of nature.\n\"When an earthquake occurs peo\nple in houses and buildings rush\nwith c-.e accord for the street,\"\nsaid Arnold. \"There seems to be a\nconviction that the outdoors is safer\nthan indoors. The outdoors, in fact,\nin a city is unsafe, for falling\nshowers of brick kill more people\nthan buildings that collapse. That\npoint should be emphasized, for the\npeople might as wen be reconciled\nto earthquakes; we always have had\nthem and always will.\n\"Th# loss of life in fire, result\ning from earthquakes should be dis\ncussed separately, for this, to my\ntaind, is a mortality which can be\novercome. Our modern office build\nings, apartment houses and homes\nmust be constructed to withstand a\n\u25a0hock of major proportion. How this\ncould and should be done in the case\n-of office buildings Is best illustrated\nby the efficacy of the foundation\nunder the Federal building in San.\n.Francisco.\nUninjured by Quake.\n\u2018This building came through the\nSan Francisco shock as nearly per\nfect as any building possibly could.\nThe ground on which it is built is\n\u2018made land;* that is, the section on\nwhich it is built was once a part of\nBan Francisco bay. Engineers, in\nlaying a foundation for the building\nlaid down a lattice work of cement\nand steel. As a result of this the\nFederal building, during the earth\nquake, moved to and fro somewhat\nas a house on rollers might shift.\n\"Loes of life in the San Francisco\nearthquake was caused mainly by\nlire and I believe the same reason\ncould be assigned for the great\ndeath rate in the Japanese catastro\nphe.\n\"Scientists are working contin\nuously to determine facts regarding\nearthquakes and I believe this work\nShould have the active support of\nthe public service corporations,\nouch as the water companies, elec\ntric light and gas corporations. The\nmovement of the earth waves\nshould and could be determined and\ngas mains, water mains and electric\nwires laid so that they would un\ndulate with- the earth movement.\nHad this been done in San Fran\ncisco the enormous loss by fire\nwould not have occurred, for water\nmains would not have been broken\nby the shock.\n\"Whether earth shocks will be\nfelt in America as a result of the\nJapanese earthquake is problem\natical. Scientists have determined\nthat earthquakes are periodical.\nThey have not, however, deter\nmined the time limit elapsing be\ntween them. We have come 'to\nexpect a succession of earthquakes\nwhen once one occurs.\nMatter of Equilibrium.\n\u201cAn earthquake, roughly speak\ning, narrows itself down to a mat\nter of equilibrium. The mountains\nin America were twice as high as\nwe see them now. Innumerable\nrains have washed the silt into\nthe ocean. This tremendous pres\nsure on the crust of the earth has\n-caused collapses of rock and other\nformation within the earth, and\nnaturally the point of least resist\nance Is a fault line in the rock.\nWhen the rock shifts it moves the\nearth in that vicinity, in other\nwords, an earthquake. Volcanoes\nare caused by earthquakes, al\nthough there are occasional erup\ntions when no earthquake is felt\non the surface.\n\"Eventually, we believe, It will be\npossible to predict earthquakes and\ntheir possible intensity. We have\nalready determined that a major\nshock is preceded by minor shocks\nof varying degrees of intensity.\n\"There is an earthquake shock\nevery day in America, but it is so\n\u25a0light that dnly the most delicately\nadjusted instruments record it.\"\numoracs is\nURGED FOR\nSCHOOLS\nJulius H. Bames Avers Many\nColleges for Women Have\nNo Such Courses.\nNEW YORK, Sept. 4.\u2014A sugges\ntion that schools should include a\ncourse in labor civics was contained\ntn a statement issued by the Insti\ntute for Public Service, of which\nJulius H. Barnes is chairman.\n\u201cOs eighty colleges for women,\nfifty-three, or nearly two-thirds,\nhave no course in labor problems,\nwhile twenty-seven give thirty-three\nlabor courses,\u201d according to the in\nstitute statement.\n\u201cImportant topics covered in these\ncourses include unemployment and\nits prevention, low wages, long\nhours, strikes and lockouts, arbitra\ntion and conciliation, accident com\npensation, sanitary and safety de\nvices, employers' associations and\nproposed solutions Of' labor prob\nlems.\n\u201cNot only do two-thirds of eighty\nwomen\u2019s colleges offer no labor\ncourses, but within the twenty\nseven women\u2019s colleges which do\noffer such courses less than one\nthird of the students actually take\nthem. Most of the courses are elec\ntive and limited to juniors and sen\niors. In thirty of eighty women\u2019s\ncolleges, however, labor facts are\nIncidentally taught as part of\ncourses in economics and history,\nthough too often these labor facts\n\u2022re a generation or a century old\n\"Os nearly 700 colleges and pro-\nLEGION PICKS GIRL, 12,\nAS MISS 1923\nfl\nfl\nF fl fl\n.JI a\nA 1 P* I\nwl a\nmK l HiHk jsfl\nJR Hi\nfl fl\nkjfl| m in\nr -fl\n1 IBBWf\nfl fl\nflflMflfl\u00df flare\nMMfIMSMEr\n'HF Jr\nfl| W fl-\nfeSK Illi V' <x> f\n\nf 'x\nTIMES STAFF, PHOTO\nMISS CATHERINE LOONEY.\nThis pretty Miss defeated several scores of young\nwomen contestants for the honor of being the prettiest girl at the\nAmerican Legion excursion at Marshall Hall Saturday. Because\nthe judges decided that she was the easiest on the eyes, she has a\nS2O gold piece. Her title will be \u201cMiss American Legion of the Dis-;\ntrict for 1923\u201d and she will be the guest at several parties being\nplanned. J.\nPOLICE BUSY ON\nDWDM ID\nALEXANDRIA\nSeries of Accidents and Liquor\nChases Feature Week-\nEnd Traffic.\nALEXANDRIA, Va\u201e Sept. 4.\nStarting Saturday afternoon and\ncontinuing up until the small hours\nof this morning, the Camp Humph\nrey\u2019s road below Alexandria was the\nscene of a series of automobile acci\ndents and other disturbances.\nConstable F. J. Weiss, of Fairfax\ncounty, made sixteen arrests during\nthis time. Among those who were\narrested and against whom the more\ngraver charges have been. placed\nare: Osbourne Fipwick, colored, of\nWashington, D. C.. who Is wanted\nin Fairfax county on the charge\nof violating the State prohibition\nlaw, arrested by Constable Weiss,\nand held In connection with the\naccident in which Theodore Rogers\nof New Alexandria, seriously\ninjured. Rogers ig in the Alexan\ndria hospital suffering from a com\npound fracture of the left leg. The\naccident occurred near Lorton, Va\u201e\nand it is alleged that Finwick failed\nto stop after striking the car\nin which Rogers was riding.\nGeorge Donald and Ulysses Bell,\nboth colored, of Washington, D. C.,\nare held on a charge of operating\nan automobile while under the influ\nence of liquor. Donald and Bell were\narrested following an accident in\nwhich the car they were driving\ncrashed into a motor bus oper\nating between Alexandria and Foit\nHumphreys and driven by David\nCrockett. It is estimated sl'so dam\nage was done to the bus. The men\nwill be removed from the Alexandria\njail to the Fairfax courthouse todav\nfor trial.\nJoseph Henderson, white, and\nArthur Dash, colored, were arrested\nSaturday by Officer Bell on the\ncharge of violating the State pro\nhibition law. It is alleged that\nwhen searched Henderson had a\nhalf pint of corn liquor on his\nperson and Dash had nearly .a quart\nof the same stuff. They were ar\nraigned before Judge Frederick G.\nDuvall and held lor the grand jury\nunder a SSOO bond.\nPermits for school attendance will\nbe issued today at the Lee School,\non Prince street. Each child desir\ning entrance must show a tax \u2019re\nceipt and a birth certificate. Per\nmits will be issued tomorrow also\nbetween the hours of 9 a. m. and\n2 p. m. Permits for the colored\nchildren will be Issued Friday.\nfessional schools for both men and\nwomen, over 500 do not advertise\nany attention whatever to labor\nproblems. The subject is almost un\nknown in the colleges which train\nteachers, and is not even part of\nthe model course of study for\nteacher training schools which is\nnow sweeping the country under\nthe leadership of the Carnegie Foun\ndation. In fact, this model course\nneither mentions nor hints at train\ning that will help teachers them\nselves study and think straight\nabout strikes, child labor, preven\ntion of business cycles, proper\nlength of the working day, protec\ntion of women and children in in\ndustry, labor education and other\nlabor civics.\u201d\nTHE WASHINGTON TIMES\nRobert Edeson Is Ill:\nCondition Called\nSerious\nLOS ANGELES, Sept. 4.\nRobert Edeson, a favorite stage\nand screen actor, is seriously ill\nat his home here, suffering\nfrom a complication of influ\nenza and blood poisoning. Mr.\nEdeson was suddenly taken sick\nseveral days ago. .while working\nin a film studio. He thought\nnothing of it, however, until\nlast night, when he grew sud\ndenly worse.\nHis wife, Mary Newcomb,\nhas been notified. She is ap\npearing in a leading role in\n\u201cThe Woman and the Jury,\u201d,\nnow playing in New York.\nMr. Edeson is one of the best\nknown actors on the American\nstage. His first starring ve\nhicle was \u2018\u2018Strongheart,\u201d which\nran for several seasons in New\nYork and on tour. He was\nforced to appear for many sea\nsons afterward in similar roles.\nHe first entered motion picture\nwork with the Vitagraph Com\npany ten years ago in their\nBrooklyn studios, and has\nplayed in them ever since inter\nmittently. His most recent work\nwas in the Zane Grey picture,\n\u2018\u2018To The Last Man,\u201d for Fa\nmous Players-Lasky.\nBUNTNEWSBOY\nWEDS BEFORE\nFRIENDS\nNEW YORK, Sept. 4.\u2014Oscar Hy\nman, the blind newsboy whose stand\nIs at Eighth street and Astor place,\nput on his dress clothes and his silk\nhat last night and took a to\nthe synagogue, where he was mar\nried to Miss Yetta Stecker after a\ncourtship which began a year ago.\nAlthough only 400 Invitations were\nissued for the ceremony the guests\nnumbered more than 1,000. In\ncluded among them were scores of\nOscar\u2019s customers, all of whom he\nrecognized by their voices when they\noffered congratulations after the\nwedding.\n\u201cYetta and I are much obliged for\nyour good wishes and for corning\nhere,\u201d said Oscar, \"and to show you\nthat we are, we are going to post\npone starting out to Lakewood on\nour honeymoon trip until after the\nmorning papers come from down\ntown. I\u2019ll wait until they come \u00abnd\nI\u2019ll see that all of my regulars get\nthem I\u201d\nMuch cheering followed, and some\nof the wedding guests, headed by\nJoe Levy, Duke of Essex street, who\nhad left his Rolls-Royce outside in\ncharge of Itchee, his Japanese chauf\nfeur-valet, pressed forward with the\nintention of kissing the bride. Oscar,\ndespite his blindness, sensed what\nwas coming and bundled her into a\nwaiting taxi and whisked her away.\n\"It was not for them to kiss her\nthat Yetta and I got married,\u201d he\nsaid.\nYetta and Oscar met each other at\na dance, and he got in his first ef\nfective work by telling her that, al\nthough he could not see, her voice\nwas so sweet that he was sure she\nmust be beautiful.\n\"Go along, you kidder!\u201d said\nYetta, who was secretly much\npleased.\nTA\u00ab National Daily\nREHABILITATION\nof urn a\nBESUM\nAmericans Familiar With Coun\ntry Think 25 Years Needed\nFor Recovery.\nBy Cosmopolitan News Service.\nNEW YORK, Sept. 4.\u2014Japan will\nrequire at least twenty-five years In\nwhich to recover fully from the\nblighting effects of the disaster, says\nCapt. Edward A. Salisbury, who has\njust returned to New York city after\na long stay In that country.\nIts lines of communication gone,\nIts naval bases destroyed, the ma\njority of its public buildings in ruins,\nJapan will be slow to regain what\npolitical and commercial prestige It\nheld in the past.\nConfronted by an unparalleled\nproperty loss and facing potential\ndamage even greater In the crippling\nof Industries, the land of the Mikado\nwill be slow in making its \"come\nback,\u201d Captain Salisbury said.\nOfficial Records Destroyed.\n\u201cI believe the destruction mani\nfest In Yokohama and Tokyo has\nbeen paralleled nowhere,\u201d he con\ntinued. \"Tokyo apparently has suf\nfered a> complete loss of her public\nbuildings, with the destruction of\nall government records, which can\nnever be replaced.\n\u201cThe'bulk of the financial loss will\nbe found to have been occasioned by\nthe destruction of the new and\nmodern business structures in that\ncity and Yokohama.\n\"The greater portions of both\nTokyo and Yokohama were built up\nof lightly constructed buildings of\nbamboo, firs, and matting, and these\nstructures must have burned like\ntinder, trapping thousands of the\noccupants like rats.\n\"There are only three or four\nmain roads leading out -of Tokyo\nnarrow, twisting thoroughfares,\nlined with blind alleys and lanes\nleading to nowhere\u2014and one can\nimagine the panic which ensued\nwhen the frightened residents at\ntempted to choke through these\nroads, carrying their worldly pos\nsessions and fighting to escape the\nflames.\nAlley Death Traps.\n\"Thousands of them must have\nbeen trampled to .death. It is. hard\nto find one\u2019s way through a Japa\nnese street even in normal times,\nand these little alleys must have\nbeen veritable death traps Saturday.\nPicture 2,600,000 crazed persons\nfighting as they sought to flee death.\n\"Japan has 4iad many small earth\nquakes during the last score of\nyears, and while the damage has\nnever been great, the people always\nwere expecting such a calamity as\novertook them Saturday.\n\u201cTokyo and Yokohama are both\nbuilt upon a huge geological fault,\nand those cities knew they would\nbe visited by disaster some day. But\nwith true Oriental fatalism, the\npeople did nothing about it\u2014just\nwaited patiently for It to come. I\nhave heard numerous predictions of\nsuch a disaster.\"\nCALLS MESS\nGHEATTST SIN\nOF BILD\nHarry G. Selfridge, London\nCapitalist and Merchant,\nDiscusses Psychology.\nBy LUTHER A. HUSTON,\nInternational News Service.\nLONDON, Sept. 4.\u2014ls you want\nto be original let your wits go wool\ngathering now and then. Your\nmind may accumulate a few cob\nwebs, but when you brush them\naway the kernel of a genuine idea\nla likely to remain.\nHarry Gordon Selfridge, the\nAmerican owner of London\u2019s most\nup-to-date department store, laid\ndown this delectable doctrine in an\naddress before a group of English\nteachers. He launded the gospel of\nhard work, but made a plea for the\nvalue of an occasional mental ex\ncursion into the realms of fancy.\n\"Imagination,\" said Selfridge, \"is\none of the qualities of the human\nmind that is most nearly Godlike.\nCan you realize anything more\ncharming than, after the day\u2019s work\nand the evening\u2019s reading are over,\nto sit In that easy chair and let\nthe mind run in the most fantastic\nmanner possible?\n\"It is nonsense, absurdity. But\nImagination is the result, and In\nthe morning, after thinking the\nthing over and brushing aside the\nunnecessary and nebulous, you will\nfind some little kernel which Is\nworth following. Imagination is\nthe mother of originality.\u201d\nOutlining to the teachers his\nideas of their privileges in connec\ntion with the Instruction of the\nyoung, Selfridge said:\n\"Teach them the value of time,\nbecause time is the only commodity\nof any kind in the world of which\nevery Individual has the same\namount. Time is the most precious\nof all things, because as we me ihe\nminutes so will the results show.\n\u201cI urge as strongly as I can\nthat young people be taught really\nto love work Work does things,\nwork accomplishes, work achieves.\nPersonally I think the greatest sin\nis laziness. The idea of going to\nsea and sitting gazing at the bkv\nfor two weeks during the year for\nthe benefit of one\u2019s health is, to\nme, a sin.\u2019\u2019-\nHELD FOR BEATING WIFE\nDESERTED 11 YEARS AGO\nPHILADELPHIA, Sept. 4.\nCharged with beating his wife while\nvisiting her, after having deserted\nher eleven years ago, Edward Mance,\nnegro, of Baltimore, was held in\nSI,OOO bail for a further hearing.\nThe wife, Mrs. Inez Mance, is m\nthe Lankenau Hospital with injuries\nreceived when she jumped from the\nsecond-floor window of her home, in\nOpal street near Poplar, to escape\nhim.\nCHILD CANNOT TALK,\nWONDER PIANIST\nI jiW IF\nstaff aaHBiW RiMMir\"' t&kn.\nBail Hv SO?\nHBr Ji BsSfof--\n\u25a0Mr\nMB\nINTERNATIONAL MWS ftSCL\nPredictions that Leo S. Kushner, twenty-seven months* old, above,\nwould become a Beethoven, are made in New York as neighbors\nlisten to piano concerts given by the child. The prodigy plays por\ntions of \u201cOver.the Waves,\u201d \u201cLa Paloma,\u201c an air from Rigoletto,\nand \u201cMinuet Militaire.\u201d These were varied by snatches from\n\u201cYankee Doodle\u201d and \u201cYea, We Have No Bananas.\u201d His* father\nsaid the child had begun when eight months old to hum airs played\nby his sister.\nMN SWERINGEN\nHAIL VENTURE\nSUCCEEDS\nRuckeyser Tells How Twin Mil\nlionaire Brothers Took Chance\nWith Nickel Plate.\nBy MERRYLE STANLEY\nRUKEYSER.\n(Copyright, 1923. Cosmopolitan Newt\nService.)\nNEW YORK, Sept. 4.\u2014Nineteen\ntwenty-three is unquestionably a\nrailroad year, and the improvement\nin earnings comes as a tentative\nvindication of the judgment of two\nventuresome brothers in Cleveland\nwho bought a railroad in 1916 when\nmost people were chanting songs\nabout the plight of the railroads.\nO. P. and M. J. Van Swerlngen,\nmillionaire bachelors, acquired con\ntrol of the New York, Chicago, and\nSt. Louis railroad. (The Nickel\nPlate) in 1916 from the New York\nCentral, and this summer with tl\\e\npermission of the Interstate Com\nmerce Commission, transformed it\ninto a larger and more powerful\nsystem by consolidating with the\nToledo, St. Louis and Western (the\nClover Leaf), the Lake Erie and\nWestern, the Chicago and State\nLine Railroad Company, and the\nFort Wayne, Cincinnati and Louis\nville Company.\nBesides creating this greater\nNickel Plate road, the Van Swer\ningens at the beginning of the year\nacquired effective control of the\nChesapeake and Ohio railroad, a\nsoft-coal carrier which feeds freight\nto the Nickel Plate, whose original\nfreight consist of food products and\nmanufactured merchandise from the\nMiddle West.\nIn order Better to co-operate with\nthe Chesapeake and Ohio the Nickel\nPlate management has laid out\na program for improving its facili\nties.\nAlready, without fanfare. the\nmanagement is proceeding to unify\nand strengthen the new Nickel\nPlate. Thirty-two miles of new\nsecond track are about to be laid\nand new and heavier rails placed\nat various points to accommodate\nthe Pcific and Mikado locomotives\nincluded in the new equipment or\ndered. AddUlonal yard trackage,\nbridge renewals, the removal of a\ngrade crossing at Cleveland and the\nInstallation of additional automatic\nblock signals on the Fort Wayne\ndivision have been authorized.\nMoreover, three new freight trains\nhave been added to the schedule, as\nthe process of knitting the consoli\ndated roads into a signal system\ncontinues.\nPITTSBURGH MAN WANTS\nBRIDE FROM KANSAS CITY\nKANSAS CITY, Mo., z Sept. 4\nMayor Gordon has sent out the dis\ntress signal of a lonely young man\nfrom Pennsylvania in search of a\nKansas City bride.\nIn a letter to the mayor, Thomas\nSeiffert, Pittsburgh, who described\nhimfcelf as thirty-one years old,\ntemperate, a business man, blue\neyed and fair of complexion, ap\npealed that some Kansas City girl\ncorrespond with him.\nSeiffert said he had lived in Kan\nsas City several years ago. and\nhad become attracted by the type\nof womanhood there.\nMARRIAGE LICENSES.\nJames Jack Callahan, 26. of Kenosha.\nWis., and Martha Jane Loop, of Norfolk.\nVa. Judge Robert E. Mattingly.\nJohn Chester Brady. 30. and Mabel, H.\nSheetz, 22. of Edinburg, Va. The Rev.\nJ, C. Geale.\nDavid John Gimber, 27. of Albany, &L-\nY., and Margaret Ellen Taylor, 21. The\nRev. M. L. Rippy.\nRobert L. Chaney, 36, and Hattie Es\ntella Rice. 24. The Rev. T. E. Davis.\nJames Reeves Bell. 34, and Mabel Lola\nElrfch, 27, both of New York city. The\nRev, H. Allen Griffith.\nWillie T. Jessie, 23, and Nannie Mae\nTaylor, IS, both of Dunbrooke, Va. The\nRev. H. F. Downs.\nArthur L. Walker, 36, and Leola S\nDavis, 30. The Rev. J. C. Ball.\nWilliam T. Foshng, 29, and Merle M.\nCrtsler, 24. The Rev. T. A. Johnstone.\nJohn D. Burrows, 24. and Clarenda\nElizabeth Wilnon, 23. The Rev. M. J.\nRiordan.\nWilfred A. Simpson, 26, and Mary\nDorothy Guilford, Hi. The Rev. C. hl.\nWheeler.\nTUESDAY, SEPTEMBER 4, 1928.\nI WHAT\u2019S POING\nToday and, Tomorrow\nToday.\nMeeting Friendship Rebekah Lodge\nNo. 8. Odd Fellow* Temple, evening.\nMeeting, Vincent B. Costello Post,\nAmerican Legton,' District Building, 8\np. m.\nConcert\u2014Army Band, Tenth and U\nstreets northwest, 7:30 p. m.\nMeeting\u2014French Class, Women\u2019s City\nClub, 6 p. m.\nMeeting\u2014Gavel Chapter. No. 29, Ma\nsonic Temple, 7:30 p. m.\nElection\u2014Officers of the Knights of\nColumbus, K. of C. Hall. 8 p. m.\nLecture\u2014\" Applied Psychology,\u201d Dr.\nDavid V. Bush, Belaaco Theater. 8:16\np. m. f\nDinner\u2014Building Exchange Associa\ntion, City Club, 8:30 p. m.\nConcert\u2014Navy Band, Vermont ave\nnue and U street northwest, 7:30 p. m.\nMeeting\u2014Catholic Daughters of Amer\nlet, Raleigh Hotel, evening.\nTomorrow.\nMeeting\u2014Friendship Temple. No. 9,\nPythian Sisters, Pythian Temple, eve\nning.\nOuting\u2014Benning Council, No. 21, Jr.\ng. U. A. M. and unity Council, No. 17.\naughters of America, Minnesota and\nGrant place, Benning. D. C., all day.\nMeeting\u2014Women's guild of the Mt.\nPleasant Congregational Church, 11 a. m.\nMeeting\u2014Areme Chapter, O. E. S.. Ma\nsonic Temple, evening.\nConcert\u2014Army Band, Walter Reed\nHosp|tal, 6:30 p. m.\nMeeting\u2014French section. Women\u2019s\nCity Club, clubhouse, 11 a. m.\nMeeting\u2014Association of Oldest Inhab\nitants Association. Union Engine House,\n8 p. m.\nLuncheon Rotary Club, Willard\nHotel, 12:30 p. m.\nLuncheon\u2014Lion Club, Willard Hotel,\n12:30 p. m.\nLuncheon\u2014Optimists Club, City Club.\n12:30* p. m.\nMeeting\u2014Electrical Contractors* As\nsociation. City Club, 12:80 p. m.\nLuncheon\u2014Purdue University Club,\nCity Club, 12:30 p. m.\nLuncheon\u2014Kiwanls Club, City Club.\n12:30- p. m.\nLuncheon \u2014Bankers\u2019 Association. City\nClub. 12:30 p. m.\nConcert Marine Band, Capitol\nGrounds, 5 p. m.\nConcert\u2014 Navy Band, Navy Yard, 7:30\np. m,\nConcert \u2014Soldiers\u2019 Home Band, band\nstand, 5:50 p. m.\nSALOON MEN REFUSE\nTO SHUT UP SHOP\nSUNBURY, Pa., Sept. 4.\u2014Seventy\nnine saloons have been ordered\nclosed in Northumberland county by\nthe Department of Justice of the\nUnited States and the attorney gen\neral' of Pennsylvania. It is said\nnone of the saloon men of Shamokin\nhave obeyed the order.\nThere are forty saloons in Shamo\nkin,. twenty-three in Mt. Carmel,\nfour, in Treverton and ten in Kulp J\nmon\u2019t. This is the largest section of\nthe mining district.\nIt is said that the State police\nand the Federal agents, traveling in\nthe district, will see to it that pad\nlocks are placed on the doors. It is\nestimated that upward of 1,000 vio\nlators of the Eighteenth Federal\nAmendment, located in five coun\nties, have been notified to remove\nat once all bar equipment, screens,\npartitions and swing doors and\ncease selling intoxicating liquors.\nShort Term Securities.\n(Furnished by W. B. Hibbs Co.)\nBid Ask.\nAlum. Co. of Am. 7s, \u201925 102% 103\u2019\nAlum. Co. of Am. 7s, \u201933 106 106%\nAm. Cotton OH 6s, 1924. 95 96\nAm. Su. Tob. cv. 7s, \u201925 96 98\nAm. Tel Tel. 6s, 1924 100% 100%\nAm. T. T. col. 4s, \u20192B 92 92%\nAm. Thread 6s, 1928. 101 102%\nAnaconda 6s, 1929 102 102%!\nAnaconda Cop. 6s, 1953. 97% 97%\nAnaconda Cop. 7s, 1938 100% 100%\nAnglo Am. Oil 7%5, 1925 102% 102%\nArmour Co. 5%5, 1995 88% 89\nB. O. Ry. col. 6s, \u201924 100% 101%\nB. O. P. L. 3%5, 1925. 95% 95%\n8.&0.5.W. Div. 3%5, \u201925 93% 94\nBell >Tel. of Can. ss, \u201925 97% 98\nBell Tel. of Can. 7s, \u201925 102% 102%\nBell Tel. of Pa. ss, \u20194B 97 98\nBethlehem St. 6s, 1948.. 98 98%\nBr. C. Mi. col. tr. 6s, \u20193l 99 99%\nCan. Nor. Ry. ss, \u201925 99 99%\nCan. Nor. Ry. 5%5, \u201924 100 100%\nCan. Nor. Ry. 6s, '24... 100% 100%\nCent. Arg. Ry. 6s, \u201927.. 97% 98% i\nCen.\nFed. Sug Ref. 6s, 1933.. 97% 97%\nHock. Valley 6s, 1924..\nKennccott 7s. 1930 102% 103\nL. S. M. S. 4s, 1931.. 92 92%\nNat. Lea. Bs. 1925 96 96%\nOr. S. L. Ref. col. 4s, \u201929 92% 92%'\nPhila. Co. 6s, 1944 100% 101\nSears Roebuck 7s, 1923. 100 100%\nSin. Co. Pur. 5%5, 1926. 96 97\nSin. Co. 6s. 1926 95% 97\nSloss Sheffield 6s, 1929.. 96% 97%\nSolvay Bs, 1927 104 104%\nSo. Pac. Con. 4s, 1929... 92 92%\nSo. N. Y. 7s. 1925-81.... 108% iOS\nSo. N. Y. 6%5, 1938 106 106%\nSwift Co. 58, 1922.... 90% 91\nUn. Pac. Con. 4s, 1927.. 96% 96%\nU. S. Rubber ss. 1947... 86% 87\nVacuum 011 7s, 1936.... 105% 106\nWestinghouse El. 7s, \u2019Bl 106% 107\nSTRICKEN JUPAN\nFELT THIOL\nSLUMP\nNation in Serious Business\nDepression When Earthquake\nDisaster Came.\nBy TOM EVERRITT,\nCosmopolitan News Service.\nDisaster stricken Japan waa mak\ning but slow progress i n recovering\nher business equilibrium which waa,\nin common with every other country\nin the world, upset by the war, ac\ncording to the Department of Com\nmerce.\nThe recent report of the depart\nment says, in part, \u201cThe financial\nsituation In Japan is marked bv in\ncreasing uneasiness and uncertainty\nas the heavy imports continue to ad\nvance the already large unfavorable\nbalance of trade, and the country\u2019s\ndepresdted Industries are a growing\nsource of anxiety to business firms.\n\"The situation may be attributed\nin part to business depression and\npolitical disturbances in countries\nwhich afford a market for Japan\u2019s\nproducts under normal conditions,\nbut business men in Japan ascribe a\nlarge part of it to the Chinese boy\ncott.\u201d\nThe high cost of living, the in\ndustrial depression and unhappy\nlabor. conditions which are accom\npanied by considerable unemploy\nment, are reflected In the report,\nwhich further says, \"At the close of\nJuly, the index figures of representa\ntive commodities stood at 254; the in\ndustrial- depression reported In June\ncontinues, and restricted production\nIs keeping pace only with the de\nmand for certain commodities in a\ndesire to avoid overstocking; the\nlabor situation has not improved.\nUnemployment is in evidence\nthroughout the country, and there\nhas been a general decrease In\nwages. Unrest and strikes are de\ncreasing. Political conditions, how\never, are quiet and favorable to\ntrade and industry.\u201d\nThe pessimistic note that run*\nthrough the entire report continue*\nin this wish, \"Th* stock market con\ntinues to reflect the depression\npreviously reported. The raw-silk\nmarket is weak and irregular. The\ndomestic demand for cotton yarn\nand cotton textiles is falling off and\nthe market is inactive. Iron and\nsteel are quiet but firm, and lumber\nis dull. An unofficial forecast indi\ncates a decline in the 1928 rice crop.\u201d\nLocal Stockes.\nSALES.\n\u25a0Washington Gas 6\u2019s, 1933, |SQO@\n10